    "body": "## Problem\r\n\r\nFixes #38955.\r\n\r\nI reproduced this in a 32 bit container (nix ftw) and then checked the first range value that should cover the whole buffer: `tree:included_ranges(true)`. On 32-bit it returned\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n{ { 0, 0, 0, -1, -1, -1 } }\r\n```\r\n\r\nwhile the same code on 64-bit returned\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n{ { 0, 0, 0, 4294967295, 4294967295, 4294967295 } }\r\n```\r\n\r\nThat told me the range was already wrong before any Lua-side logic ran.\r\n\r\nI found that the problem was in the treesitter binding layer, where `TSRange` fields were being pushed through Lua integers here (pretty cool that github shows the code preview):\r\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/71ac4db335e00b03b27d2c4aa5ab90c083a3a3e7/src/nvim/lua/treesitter.c#L471-L492\r\n\r\nand read back the same way here:\r\nhttps://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/71ac4db335e00b03b27d2c4aa5ab90c083a3a3e7/src/nvim/lua/treesitter.c#L608-L642\r\n\r\nThat immediately turns the whole-buffer end values into `-1` on 32-bit systems.\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\n\r\nRound-trip those values through Lua as numbers and validate them before converting them back into `uint32_t`.\r\n",
    "closed_at": "2026-04-16T07:59:21Z",
